column169: Description Of Events

AT THE UPS MIAMI FLORIDA FACILITY, ONE BLACK SHRINKED WRAPPED WOODEN SKID SHIPPING AIR CARGO SERVICE TO COLOMBIA WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN FLAMMABLE PRODUCTS. DURING THE SCREENING PROCESS WHILE CUTTING THE BLACK SHRINK WRAPPING, SEVERAL BOXES WERE FOUND WITH CLASS NINE DIAMOND LABELS AND AIR LIMITED QUANTITY MARKS. OTHER BOXES WERE FOUND WITH GROUND LIMITED QUANTITY MARKS. INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS OF THESE BOXES FOUND NUMEROUS FLAMMABLE PERFUMERY PRODUCTS. THE FREIGHT WAS OFFERED FOR AIR TRANSPORTATION TO UPS AIR CARGO WITHOUT ANY DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BLACK SHRINK WRAPPING. THERE WAS NO INDICATION ON THE AIR WAYBILL THAT DANGEROUS GOOD PRODUCTS WERE BEING SHIPPED AIR SERVICE.  THE ISSUING CARRIER'S AGENT NAME AND CITY ON THE AIR WAYBILL IS ALSEATRANS US, 1665 NW 102ND AV, SUITE 108, MIAMI FL, 33172, US. THE SHIPPER'S NAME AND ADDRESS ON THE AIR WAYBILL IS MSL INTL GROUP, LLC, 1665 NW 102ND AV, MIAMI FL US.

On August 13, 2024, at 2050 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Roadrunner personnel in Conley, Georgia regarding the release of Socar Brake Wash (UN1208, Hexanes, 3, II). Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 20 gallons of Socar Brake Wash (UN1208, Hexanes, 3, II) from (1) 55-gallon DM. The release was caused by a forklift puncture and impacted a 15ft x 20ft area of concrete on the dock floor. Contractors reported that the release had completely evaporated by the time they arrived. Contractors placed the damaged drum with the remaining product into a 65-gallon metal overpack then staged the waste onsite for proper disposal.

column169: Possible thermal runaway of a lithium ion battery occurred on flight AA 6271 ALB-ORD on 8/1/2024. CRJ 700 aircraft, N750SK  During the flight the AFT Flight Attendant sat in her jumpseat. At some point during this action, her Electronic Flight Attendant Device (iPhone 12) slid from her pocket and into the gap behind the folding jumpseat. She stood up and realized the phone may have been crunched/damaged in the jumpseat. She noticed a crack in the device's screen.  A few moments later she noticed the phone began to feel warm. She notified the FWD flight attendant of the issue. Together, they took the device to a galley ice tray and drowned the device in ice water and notified the flight deck. At that point, they realized they should be using the aircraft's fire containment bag. They moved the device to the fire containment bag and added more liquid to completely drown the device. Upon arrival into ORD, the fire containment bag containing the damaged device was handed off to a customer service agent. There were no further issues with the damaged device. PLEASE NOTE that the device DID NOT emit smoke, sparks, flames, or any gasses. This should be considered a possible dangerous evolution of heat.

On Monday, August 5, 2024, a CN mechanical performing an inspection observed that the bottom outlet valve appeared to be leaking from tank car # FURX 160111 along with a strong Ethanol type odor in the area. The employee notified the Waterloo Yard Master who in turn notified the CN Dangerous Goods Team. The tank car was set out to an isolation track (WA60) for inspection by a CN emergency response contractor.  A CN emergency response contractor was dispatched to the location for mitigation. The contractor performed an inspection of the tank car and found the bottom outlet valve to be leaking from the threads of the bottom outlet valve cap. It was determined that there was a failure in the sealing surface of the valve seat to include a defective gasket. (The BOV cap was found to be less than tool tight and the BOV in the closed position and pinned upon initial inspection). CN emergency response contractor did observe cable seal to be correctly in place. The BOV cap was removed, and it was observed to be leaking past the closed ball.  The BOV valve handle was cycled several times to the open and closed position to free any debris that may have been trapped in the BOV sealing surface potentially causing the leak. The BOV cap was then removed and observed for 20 minutes to ensure there was no further leakage from the valve. It was noted that the BOV cap gasket was deformed and was replaced. The bottom outlet valve cap was then re-installed and tightened with a 36" pipe wrench. Upon tightening the BOV cap, CN emergency response contractor proceeded to place new cable seals on the BOV / Cap.

On August 5, 2024, at 1631 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Des Moines, Iowa regarding the release of Lactic Acid (UN3265, 8, III). Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of Lactic Acid (UN3265, Corrosive Liquid, acidic, organic, n.o.s., 8, III) from (9) 275-gallon IBC plastic totes. The release was caused by a rollover accident and impacted the trailer floor, and an area of soil. Contractors placed neutralizer and absorbents on the soil in preparation for remedial and restorative activities, and the totes and trailer were transported to a nearby tow facility. At the tow facility there was an additional release of material that impacted a trail of concrete and the inside of a roll-off. Contractors neutralized, and cleaned all impacted areas with absorbents, then transferred the remaining product from the damaged totes into new totes. All waste was collected and containerized in (11) 55-gallon DF’s and (9) 275-gallon IBC plastic totes, then staged onsite for proper disposal.

column169: Operations Supervisor I Nathan ODonnell contacted safety to report that trailer 572156 caught on fire while on the 241/RDG yard. Operations Supervisor I Nathan ODonnell stated that after ABF Road Driver Terry Schreck arrived at 241/RDG the lead trailer 572156 started smoking. ABF Road Driver Terry S chreck advised that after he arrived at 241/RDG he was about to unhook his set when he noticed the lead trailer 572156 was smoking. ABF Road Driver Terry Schreck advised that he then proceeded to disconnect rear trailer 500713 and converter gear 71708 from the lead trailer. ABF Road Driver Terry Sch reck advised that he then proceeded to move trailer 572156 to the middle of the yard before he disconnected the trailer from tractor 13383. ABF Road Driver Terry Schreck advised that after he disconnected trailer 572156 from the tractor the Reading Fire Department arrived on scene. Deputy Chief Glor e of the Reading Fire Department advised that he believes a pallet of Lithium Ion Batteries shifted during transit. Deputy Chief Glore advised that the battery post may have contacted metal causing them to arc igniting a pallet of writing pens that were incased in carboard that was loaded underneath  the pallet of Lithium Ion Batteries. Deputy Chief Glore advised that the Reading Fire Department was able to put the fire out and made sure no drains or waterways were impacted. Operations Supervisor I Nathan ODonnell advised he will send photos of the damage to safety. Safety contacted CURA and sp oke with Cameron Kerr to conduct cleanup procedures.

column169: PACKAGE ORIGINALLY ARRIVED IN TO LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY UPS WORLDPORT OPERATIONS ON 11-MAY-2024 WHERE IT WAS STAGED FOR CLEARANCE FROM CUSTOMS. PACKAGE WAS RETAINED BY CUSTOMS UNTIL UPS WORLDPORT RESPONDED TO THE IMPORT INSPECT AREA DUE TO THE CUSTOMS AGENT DISCOVERY OF THE UNDECLARED PRODUCTS ON 18-AUGUST-24. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS, UPS DISCOVERED (20) FLAMELESS RATION HEATERS CLASSIFIED AS 4.3 DANGEROUS WHEN WET. NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX. THIS PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED USING UPS ACCOUNT NUMBER 7V077R, GAIN COSMETIC CO LTD, RM 201, 9, YONGGOK-RO 20BEON-GIL, YANGJI-MYEON, YONGIN 17161 SOUTH KOREA.

Hazardous material package containing four one-gallon jugs of hurricane heavy duty degreaser (UN3266) that had been placed in an undeclared overpack box that had no Hazardous material markings or identifiers since it had no markings, it went up the conveyor belt as a normal package causing unnecessary handling resulting in the degreaser to spill.

UNLOADER NOTICED HAZMAT PACKAGE LEAKING ON CONVERYOR BELT. UNLOADER NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR AND SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED RMP TO SEND DOWN RESPONDER. RESPONDER ARRIVES AT THE SPILL WITH PPE ON, DECISION TREE, AND STOCKED SPILL CART. RESPONDER CONTAINS LEAKING PACKAGE AND OTHER LEAKED ON PACKAGES. CLEANS UP REST OF SPILL.

column169: Package was found on van line appearing fully undamaged but with a strong chemical odor. Manager isolated package from sort immediately upon discovery due to strong odor, despite package not being labeled as a hazmat. QA investigated package and discovered it was an undeclared hazmat item. Outer packaging would be sufficient for hazmat item within, but is not labeled. Item was placed inside plastic bag within box, but has no additional packing material. Appears likely item moved freely within box, causing dents and forcing liquid to spill via lid seams. Leak fully contained within package.

On August 12, 2024, at 1321 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in East St. Louis, Illinois regarding the release of Eterset 2950 (UN1866, Resin Solution, 3, III). Contractors were dispatched to the site to perform all onsite clean-up activities. Upon arrival, contractors confirmed the release of 5 ounces of ETERSET 2950 from (1) 55-gallon DM that impacted a 5ft x 5ft area of the trailer floor. Contractors could not determine the cause of the release. Contractors placed the damaged drum with residual product in an overpack to be forwarded on to the original consignee, then cleaned the release with absorbents and the proper PPE. All waste was containerized in (1) 5-gallon DF and taken offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

During a customer site pickup, an incident occurred involving a drum of Isopropanol. A Veolia employee was reorganizing the box truck when the accident happened. While using a drum cart to relocate the Isopropanol container, the drum was improperly secured and fell backwards onto the cart. As a result, one of the cart's forks punctured the drum.  The puncture caused approximately 2 gallons of Isopropanol to spill. Prompt action was taken to address the situation. The spilled material was thoroughly cleaned up and disposed of in accordance with proper procedures. To prevent further leakage, the damaged drum was placed inside an overpack container.
column170: This incident highlights the importance of proper drum handling and securement techniques during transportation and storage operations.   Following the incident, a safety briefing was conducted with all Veolia field service personnel. The briefing emphasized two key points:  1) The importance of regularly inspecting and maintaining material handling equipment to ensure it is in proper working condition; and   2) The critical need to securely fasten all packages, containers, and drums during any movement or transportation.  This reminder aimed to reinforce best practices in handling hazardous materials and prevent similar incidents in the future. Management stressed that these safety protocols are essential for protecting employees, customers, and the environment from potential hazards associated with chemical spills or leaks.

On August 2, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN1760 was crushed in transit and released approximately thirty (30) gallons of product to the trailer interior, surrounding cargo asphalt, and nearby catch basin. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. A drum head vacuum was used to collect and containerize approximately 100 gallons of UN1760 impacted water from the catch basin of the storm drain into two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal. It was determined that the product remained contained to the catch basin and did not migrate or threaten to impact any waters of the state. Granular absorbents, absorbent pads, and neutralizer were used to remediate the impacted surfaces. The damaged drum was overpacked into one (1) 85 gallons drum for disposal purposes. All UN1760 impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) additional 55-gallon drum for disposal purposes.

column169: The package was discovered while offloading the first inbound trailer of the day during the start of pre-load sort at around 3:15am wet/leaking.  The package was then placed into a line bin & brought to QA for processing.  Upon inspecting the packages exterior, the shipping label had a "No-Air" marking underneath the ground symbol, & and a slip that contained a Safety Data Sheet for the contents inside was found on one side of the box.  It was also discovered that the package did not have any Hazmat/Hazmat paperwork &/or Limited Quantity markings on the package which raised some concerns.  Upon opening the package 4 1-gallon cans of Seal For Life Industries Temper Kote 1000 41 Silver Industrial Heat Coating were found soiled & with the lids popped off causing them to leak contents.  3 out of 4 were also badly bent/dented & crushed on several areas of the can.  None of the 4 cans had paint clips to help prevent the lids from popping off & no packing material was inside the package to protect the cans exteriors. According to Spidr image the package appeared to be unharmed when viewing overhead images of the package at MIDD hub, meaning the package may have loaded improperly & damaged in transit as a result.  When referencing Section 14 under DOT classification in the Safety Data Sheet it was discovered the contents are classified as Packing Group 2 & as a Class 3 Flammable Liquid.  Several packages were leaked on as a result of the spill but were able to be successfully repacked.  The portion of the leftover cardboard from the repacks were held at the QA cage to be placed into the line salvage drum per cleanup.  The Improper Shipping Form & Damaged Package Report were filled out.  Contents & cardboard were placed into a line salvage drum & sealed.  Large rubber green gloves & blue nitrile examination gloves were used when handing the hazardous material & an additional line bin was used as a precautionary measure.

Forklift operator forked two drums from the shipment and supervisor called our consultant Hazmat-ONE to arrange cleanup. Spill was neutralized, waste put into waste drum, and punctured drums were placed into overpack containers.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES CONTAINED IN EQUIPMENT INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: On Aug 8th, a package was noticed during the PM sort to be emitting a small amount of smoke and had a burning smell.    After opening the package they discovered one of the smaller packages in side had burned through, causing scorch marks on other inner containers as well as a burned hole in the inner support material. The package contained cellphones, other lithium batteries as well as misc phone related accessories.  The fire had burned itself out by then and the package was isolated to ensure no further conflagration occured.   No injuries were reported.    After the package had cooled down it was placed into a steel salvage drum and is being held pending further investigation.

column43: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column169: QA personnel was called to Trailer #830652 for a potential HAZMAT package that was leaking; inspection of package verified that there was a leak of a Class 8 HAZMAT containing four individual 1 gallon jugs of sulfuric acid from the DIYchemicals/Cheboys brand. Package was isolated into a red tote and removed to the station HAZMAT cage to begin damaged package process for HAZMATs. Further inspection of the package interior verified that one out of four bottles of sulfuric acid had a loosened safety cap, resulting in the gradual spill of its contents inside the package, which remained mostly contained inside the package. Some of the cardboard box the items came in was eaten away from the spillage. There was also little to no inner packing material inside the package securing the hazardous items; there was a little bit of bubble packaging material inside, but not enough to secure the bottles, which allowed for space inside for the items to move around inside the package during transport, which resulted in damage and spillage occurring.

column169: at 0100 hrs. while inspecting their train, the WLE Gambrinus Yard train crew, noticed tank car TILX 305022 at Gambrinus Yard leaking vapor from the top of the car.  They notified the WLE Gambrinus Yardmaster who then contacted myself, John Vergis, Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE.  When I arrived, I could her the car leaking vapor from on top the car.  The leak was substantial, but just vapor, no liquid. I climbed the car and removed seal # 0672272 from the protective housing lid.  I investigated and found no leak inside the protective housing.  Upon further investigation, it was concluded that the leak was coming from the gasket connection between the pressure plate and the tank car nozzle.  The pressure plate stud bolts appeared to be tight.  There was no way to stop the leak.  The leak was coming from the left side of the housing.   I called CHEMTREC at 0127 hrs. to make a report and have them contact Marathon Petroleum in order to give me assistance.  Jennifer Johnson, the emergency contact from Marathon called me at 0158 to inquire about the report.  The CHEMTREC Report number was 2024080100010.  I told her what was going on and that I would be calling 911 to request the Stark County HAZMAT Team.  I also told her that I would be calling Enviroserve out of North Canton, Ohio to come out and do an emergency transfer of the car since that was the only way we could stop it from leaking.  She agreed and had me make the calls.  I called 911 at 0210 hrs.  I called the Timken Steel Security folks to have them stop all traffic on their access road that parralels the location of the incident, so that they would be no chance for ignition from any of their equipment.  I called Enviroserve at 0219 hrs. and briefed them on the situation and told them we needed and emergency transfer and then a flaring and purging of the car afterwards.   I called the Stark County Spill Report Line at 0234 hrs. to report the incident.  After we got the HAZMAT Team out and started doing air monitoring, I called to make a report with the Ohio EPA at 0505 just as a courtesy to report the vapor release.  We had 7 area rays set up for air monitoring and discovered that the vapors were going straight up and not really concentrating around the car or anywhere else at ground level.  No evacuations were required since the yard itself is isolated.  We started to Transload the car at about 0800 hrs.  We started to flare the car of its residual vapors at about 1430 hrs. and finished at 2230 hrs.  The car was labeled with Do Not Load and Home Shop Stickers and was stenciled “Cleaned”.

On 8/21/2024 at approximately 0900, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 9327095 at the Ground facility in Fairfield, reporting an undeclared dangerous goods spill. The shipment consisted of four (4) 1-gallon containers packaged together in one fiberboard box.  The package appeared damp on its topside.  Further investigation revealed the inner containers, marked to match the label on the outside of the package, identifying the commodity as Xylenes, a fully regulated dangerous goods commodity.  The shipment adorned no other markings, labeling, or paperwork.  The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

column169: The package was discovered while offloading the first inbound trailer of the day during the start of pre-load sort at around 3:15am wet/leaking.  The package was then placed into a line bin & brought to QA for processing.  Upon inspecting the packages exterior, the shipping label had a "No-Air" marking underneath the ground symbol, & and a slip that contained a Safety Data Sheet for the contents inside was found on one side of the box.  It was also discovered that the package did not have any Hazmat/Hazmat paperwork &/or Limited Quantity markings on the package which raised some concerns.  Upon opening the package 4 1-gallon cans of Seal For Life Industries Temper Kote 1000 41 Silver Industrial Heat Coating were found soiled & with the lids popped off causing them to leak contents.  3 out of 4 were also badly bent/dented & crushed on several areas of the can.  None of the 4 cans had paint clips to help prevent the lids from popping off & no packing material was inside the package to protect the cans exteriors. According to Spidr image the package appeared to be unharmed when viewing overhead images of the package at MIDD hub, meaning the package may have loaded improperly & damaged in transit as a result.  When referencing Section 14 under DOT classification in the Safety Data Sheet it was discovered the contents are classified as Packing Group 2 & as a Class 3 Flammable Liquid.  Several packages were leaked on as a result of the spill but were able to be successfully repacked.  The portion of the leftover cardboard from the repacks were held at the QA cage to be placed into the line salvage drum per cleanup.  The Improper Shipping Form & Damaged Package Report were filled out.  Contents & cardboard were placed into a line salvage drum & sealed.  Large rubber green gloves & blue nitrile examination gloves were used when handing the hazardous material & an additional line bin was used as a precautionary measure.

On 8/7/2024 1 pallet of UN 1789 Hydrochloric Acid(Muriatic Acid) was sitting in the SEFL BTR OS&D Bay. The pallet containing 84 boxes with 2 each 1 gallon bottles inside collapsed& fell over. The pallet collapsing caused an estimated 10 gallons to spill on the dock. The spill was contained by dock associates. SEFL Safety was contacted, and contacted Hazmat 1 spill response. E3/OMI arrived on site at approximately 9:15. The team accessed the situation& proceeded with the clean up process. Clean up was complete at approximately 13:30. In total 10-55 gallon drums were used to contain the waste.E3/OMI will return to pick up the waste drums at a later date, once approval has been received.

I asked him to bring it to us while I retrieved the TCB. He brought it to the cdt galley where FA Vanak took pictures and went to the front to share them with the purser and captain. I placed the unit temporarily in the TCB without breaking the seal awaiting further instructions and checking the eFAOM. The unit was not hot or Ieaking. We returned the battery to the passenger upon deplaning and advised him to dispose of it properly. We were advised by MX that since we did not need to break the seal on the zipper Of the TCB it could be returned to its stowed position.
